raw._content: EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AFIE) -- While area temperatures soared to the mid-nineties, snow fell on the Air Force's F-22 Raptor during weather testing in the 46th Test Wing's McKinley's Climatic Laboratory here recently. In the laboratory, test engineers can create a blizzard blowing snow; a deluge of rain, including freezing rain; stifling desert heat; humid, muggy heat; salt fog and sand storms, according to Kirk Velasco, climatic laboratory team leader. Temperatures in the laboratory can range from a frigid minus 105 degrees to blistering 165 degrees. The snow is one of many elements the Raptor will endure as part of a three-month series of grueling weather conditions tests ranging from extreme cold to desert-baking heat. Tests should end by mid to late August. McKinley Climatic Laboratory is the world's largest environmental testing chamber and can produce almost any weather condition in the world. (U.S Air Force photo)
